WEBVTT

00:09.440 --> 00:13.420
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:30.000 --> 00:35.060
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:37.900 --> 00:39.500
And here are your hosts.

00:43.940 --> 00:49.240
This is David Carson and Daryl Lane. British-born author James P. Hogan has gained a reputation

00:49.240 --> 00:52.260
as one of the premier writers of hard science fiction working today.

00:52.700 --> 00:57.440
He's published seven novels so far, including In Here at the Stars, The Gentle Giants of

00:58.140 --> 01:03.680
Giant Star, Thrice Upon a Time, The Two Faces of Tomorrow, and his latest voyage from yesteryear.

01:04.060 --> 01:05.700
Hogan tells us how he became an author.

01:06.780 --> 01:15.600
When I left school when I was 16 and wanted to be a writer then, I guess it was something that I

01:15.600 --> 01:22.180
always enjoyed doing as a kid at school. In the essays and the story writing exercises you get.

01:24.320 --> 01:27.860
And when I left school I told the world I was going to be a writer.

01:29.020 --> 01:37.400
And it seemed a good idea until somebody said, well, with all the accumulated wisdom and experience

01:37.400 --> 01:42.000
of 16 years, what are you going to write about that the world is breathlessly waiting to hear?

01:43.320 --> 01:46.360
And I hadn't thought about that and the answer was not a lot.

01:47.060 --> 01:52.460
So I went away into engineering and electronics and computers and things like that for something like

01:52.460 --> 02:01.580
20 years. And I suppose the interest in writing probably never went away.

02:02.460 --> 02:07.600
For 20 years, Hogan worked as a systems designer for computers and sold computers to scientists

02:07.600 --> 02:08.840
for use in their research.

02:09.360 --> 02:13.560
Associating with scientists as he did, Hogan was exposed to all sorts of current scientific

02:13.560 --> 02:18.020
research and he would make use of his scientific contacts when he began to write seriously.

02:19.160 --> 02:25.340
I made use of my customers pretty freely as consultants, which was kind of handy.

02:25.620 --> 02:31.960
I found that I had customers who were brain surgeons and other customers who were studied pieces of

02:31.960 --> 02:38.500
rock brought back from the Apollo missions and other guys who were building in or investigating

02:38.500 --> 02:45.140
machine intelligence. And just about any of the topics or the favorite themes of science fiction

02:45.140 --> 02:51.860
that you could take out of a hat, the chances were sort of not 10 to 1. I had a customer

02:51.860 --> 02:57.040
specializing in that field and I just had to, if I needed some background information on a

02:57.040 --> 03:02.220
particular topic, I could almost guarantee I had a phone number in my diary as a guy who could

03:02.220 --> 03:09.160
talk all day about it. And they love doing it as well. I used to call them and they like to come

03:09.160 --> 03:15.880
and talk to you tomorrow. Well, we're a little busy, but what's it about? Oh, I need some help with

03:15.880 --> 03:19.880
the book I'm working on. Well, why didn't you say so? What times do you want to show up? And they

03:19.880 --> 03:31.200
talk all day. I think this is one of the interesting sites of selling computers into

03:31.740 --> 03:39.460
this kind of area. You can imagine some of these specialists, they talk to bacteria all day long

03:39.460 --> 03:45.620
or whatever and they end up shutting the back rooms of universities. And maybe there are four

03:45.620 --> 03:52.300
people on the planet they can talk to who understand their language. And sometimes they find it hard

03:52.300 --> 04:00.100
to believe that somebody from the world outside that has walked in off the street is sincerely

04:00.780 --> 04:06.980
interested to sit down and talk to them and is curious and he wants to know what they're doing,

04:07.080 --> 04:11.840
wants to have it explained. So writing about his experiences with scientists,

04:12.340 --> 04:19.280
Hogan found that he was a science fiction writer. I didn't particularly set out to be a science

04:19.280 --> 04:25.480
fiction writer. I suppose I became one by accident. I just always wanted to write and started writing

04:25.480 --> 04:32.200
stories about the little bit of life that I'd had some personal experience of and was told I was a

04:32.200 --> 04:37.260
science fiction writer and I said, how's that? They said, well, the publisher is publishing it under

04:37.260 --> 04:42.560
their science fiction influence. So we guess you have to be so I said, okay. And it kind of started

04:42.560 --> 04:48.600
out like that. Hogan's books are scientifically accurate and highly realistic. He's been called

04:48.600 --> 04:53.160
The Man Who Put Science Back into Science Fiction. Next time we'll talk to James P. Hogan about some

04:53.160 --> 05:05.380
of his novels. This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin

05:05.380 --> 05:09.940
Science Fiction Association produced in conjunction with Odessa College in Odessa, Texas.

