06:25.880 --> 06:31.040
This is Daryl Lane and David Carson. James P. Hogan's 1977 science fiction novel,

06:31.140 --> 06:35.620
Inherit the Stars, should be required reading for anyone who demands scientific accuracy in

06:35.620 --> 06:40.780
an exciting narrative. The book takes place some 50 years in the future. A skeleton inside a spacesuit

06:40.780 --> 06:45.580
is found on the moon. That's interesting enough. But what follows is even more provocative. The

06:45.580 --> 06:50.980
skeleton is a human one and it's been on the moon for 50,000 years. The scientific unraveling of this

06:50.980 --> 06:56.000
mystery forms the basis of the novel. It's like a detective story and Hogan talks about the origins

06:56.000 --> 07:05.100
of the idea. 2001 was one of the factors that inspired me to write Inherit the Stars. I love the

07:05.100 --> 07:12.180
idea of something being found, a mystery being uncovered in the course of lunar exploration

07:12.930 --> 07:18.180
that was sufficiently intriguing to motivate a lot of scientists into unraveling it.

07:19.000 --> 07:27.180
It seemed a good opportunity to set the scientific detective story that I wanted to write.

07:27.900 --> 07:32.280
You know, okay, let's have the detective story or the mystery that the detectives are trying to

07:32.280 --> 07:38.900
solve hinge around something that's turned up on the moon. Well, dead bodies are always pretty good

07:38.900 --> 07:47.860
for detective stories. It ought to be a more interesting dead body than the standard detective

07:47.860 --> 07:54.040
thriller. So let's make it 50,000 years old and human, which raises the whole, opens up the whole

07:54.040 --> 07:59.880
bag of worms. And let's just see how they unravel that. And I wanted the ending to be

08:02.400 --> 08:09.460
a bit of a twist, a bit unexpected, a bit of a surprise, but nevertheless plausible and

08:09.460 --> 08:13.940
rational within the context of the story. I didn't want to bring in mystical agencies or

08:18.360 --> 08:22.520
strange laws of physics or anything like this to hold it together.

08:23.440 --> 08:27.820
The entire scientific community of Earth starts to work on the baffling problem of the

08:27.820 --> 08:33.040
space-suited 50,000 year old human skeleton, which they name Charlie. They soon find remnants on the

08:33.040 --> 08:38.560
moon of Charlie's culture, a map of an unfamiliar planet, scraps of Charlie's diary in an unfamiliar

08:38.560 --> 08:43.800
language, and some technological artifacts. With such clues, the scientists begin to piece

08:43.800 --> 08:49.080
together the incredible story of who Charlie was and why he was human. Hogan says the book sort of

08:49.080 --> 08:54.160
defines what science is all about. It counters some of the distorted images of scientists Hogan has

08:54.160 --> 09:00.420
seen in fiction. Scientists were always eccentric and they wore odd colored shoes and they drew

09:00.420 --> 09:06.720
cabbages that ate people and they wanted to conquer the world or something. And there are these

09:06.720 --> 09:14.180
kind of cute public impressions of scientists as people who run down the street with no clothes

09:14.180 --> 09:29.700
on shouting Eureka. Or you read phrases like it came to him in a flash and you read on and

09:30.660 --> 09:35.600
what came to him in a flash would have been enough to keep Einstein busy for the next 20 years.

09:36.380 --> 09:44.340
And real science, you know, there are insights, there are strokes of genius, but the overwhelming

09:45.380 --> 09:51.380
bulk of the work is done by a lot of unsung heroes, a lot of people doing nothing really

09:51.380 --> 09:58.020
dramatic or exciting, but just meticulously sifting through details, collecting information.

09:59.020 --> 10:04.580
For generations and for centuries, all different parts of the world. And it's really like putting

10:04.580 --> 10:11.140
together a huge jigsaw puzzle, lots of people cutting out pieces and pushing them around and

10:11.140 --> 10:16.280
every now and again somebody will take a huge chunk in this corner and see that it fits with a huge

10:16.280 --> 10:22.980
chunk down there and that's a breakthrough. And so it goes on. And it really is a detective story.

10:23.280 --> 10:25.920
I think it's a far more exciting one than most detective fiction.

10:26.500 --> 10:30.620
We strongly recommend you read Inherit the Stars to find out the solution to the mystery

10:30.620 --> 10:35.800
surrounding Charlie. Hogan wrote two sequels to Inherit the Stars and all three form a trilogy

10:35.800 --> 10:41.120
that presents an awesome view of man's origins. Next time we'll talk with Hogan about those other two books.

