12:30.920 --> 12:36.460
When I wrote Inherit the Stars I had three books in mind. I had a trilogy in mind.

12:38.120 --> 12:43.460
So I put the hooks in, although Inherit the Stars was a complete story in itself,

12:44.000 --> 12:48.320
you know, it didn't leave anything, it didn't leave the reader hanging. It told and it started

12:48.320 --> 12:53.400
and told and finished a story. Nevertheless, there were a couple of hooks in there that invited

12:53.400 --> 13:03.900
some questions, which sort of paved the way to a follow-up book. And my thinking at the time was,

13:04.060 --> 13:11.800
I'll go that far, but I won't write the second book until I have some feedback as to how the

13:11.800 --> 13:19.600
readers liked the first one. And I got a lot of mail and they all liked it and a lot of them

13:19.600 --> 13:24.700
said in their letters, will there be a follow-up? They picked out the hooks. So I wrote The Gentle

13:24.700 --> 13:30.320
Giants. The Gentle Giants of the title are a race of aliens that first turned up in Inherit the

13:30.320 --> 13:34.880
Stars. In that book, scientists from Earth had discovered a wrecked spaceship on Ganymede,

13:35.160 --> 13:39.580
one of Jupiter's huge moons. And on it were the remains of prehistoric creatures from Earth,

13:39.580 --> 13:45.160
dinosaurs and the like. In The Gentle Giants of Ganymede, humans meet some live Ganymians who

13:45.160 --> 13:49.740
have returned to the solar system after a mishap in space kept them away for some 25 million years

13:49.740 --> 13:54.500
due to time dilation. It turns out that the Ganymians had been responsible for human evolution.

13:55.140 --> 13:59.140
They'd taken primitive hominids from Earth 25 million years ago and moved them to a planet

13:59.140 --> 14:04.760
called Minerva. Minerva was then one of the inner planets of our solar system, but it was destroyed

14:04.760 --> 14:08.920
in a tremendous war involving the human stock that had evolved from the Ganymian experiments.

14:09.660 --> 14:13.960
The second book ends with the Ganymians leaving the solar system in search of their own people,

14:14.240 --> 14:17.860
who migrated from Minerva millions of years before the war that destroyed the planet.

14:18.340 --> 14:20.300
Hogan says readers wanted a third book.

14:21.740 --> 14:28.040
And they wanted another one and I did have a trilogy in mind when I wrote it. And the third one

14:28.040 --> 14:34.180
in that series is now written. It's called Giant Star and it will be, it's a July title,

14:34.700 --> 14:41.040
so it should start to appear in the bookstores around June. It's the third and last, it won't be

14:41.040 --> 14:48.000
any more in that series. So it ties up a few of the loose ends, tells another story,

14:52.100 --> 15:02.620
continues with the characters we met in the previous two books, both the terrestrial and the

15:12.200 --> 15:12.720
one.

15:12.720 --> 15:17.480
Giant Star was published in 1981 and as Hogan said, it wraps up all the mysteries and loose ends

15:17.480 --> 15:22.540
raised in the first two books. And it presents an absolutely breathtaking concept of man's origins,

15:23.320 --> 15:28.040
explaining also where man gets his curious nature, his aggressiveness, and his incredible

15:28.040 --> 15:33.100
instinct for survival. Hogan talks about the underlying purpose of the whole trilogy.

15:33.960 --> 15:40.460
Basically it was an attempt to depict science as it is, or at least as I perceive it.

15:41.120 --> 15:46.640
And at the same time weave that into a story that people who were non-scientists, non-specialists,

15:46.720 --> 15:54.120
would find stimulating and arousing for the curiosity, even if

15:56.340 --> 16:02.400
without trying to turn it into a 250-page lab report or something like that.

16:03.460 --> 16:07.620
And stimulating the books certainly are. For sheer grandeur, the whole Minervan trilogy,

16:08.000 --> 16:11.740
as some have called it, is matched by a few other works in the field of science fiction.

16:12.120 --> 16:17.480
Isaac Asimov's Foundation trilogy comes to mind as a comparison, as does Olaf Stapleton's Arjan.

16:18.060 --> 16:22.700
James B. Hogan's Inherit the Stars, The General Giants of Ganymede, and Giant Star.

16:23.440 --> 16:26.160
Contemporary science fiction has little to offer that's any better.

